    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm studying for my private pilot written exam and I'm a bit stuck on the pitot-static system. Can you explain exactly how a pitot tube works to measure airspeed, and why the pressure differential is so important? Also, what happens if the tube gets partially blocked?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A pitot tube is a sensor in the airspeed indicator system that measures airflow speed by sensing the change in air pressure between a static port and a static pitot port. The static port is usually located flush with the fuselage, while the static pitot port is pitot tube connected to the fuselage, allowing the air to pass freely in all directions. When air flows over the pitot tube, the pressure difference between the pitot and static ports creates a pressure differential, which is then converted to an airspeed reading. If the tube gets partially blocked, it can generate incorrect readings, especially at low speeds, as the blocked air has a lower-pressure side, causing the airspeed reading to become overestimated.",
