    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. that makes sense. so u said the readings become overestimated if it's blocked.. can u explain that part a bit more? like, what exactly is happening inside the lines or at the tube itself that makes the gauge jump up like that? and is it possible for a blockage to make it read zero speed instead?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When the pitot tube is partially blocked, the air flowing over the blocked section creates a region with high velocity and lower pressure, which increases the pressure difference between the pitot and static ports. As a result, the airspeed reading on the gauge overestimates the actual airspeed, since the pressure differential is exaggerated. This can cause the needle to jump up on most airspeed gauges, and the display may become erratically. It is theoretically possible for a blockage to induce an overestimation of zero speed, but this is usually not the case, as a blockage would typically create a high-pressure area, making airspeed indication more likely to be low and positive, rather than reading zero.",
